01:23:49,280 --> 01:23:50,474
What is it?

1247
01:24:00,800 --> 01:24:02,995
Please tell me you haven't
come with condolences.

1248
01:24:03,800 --> 01:24:05,995
No, I was just wondering

1249
01:24:06,200 --> 01:24:07,519
- if you wanted some com...
- What?

1250
01:24:08,440 --> 01:24:12,069
I said I was just wondering
if you wanted some company.

1251
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:20,752
I suppose life must go on.

1252
01:24:21,040 --> 01:24:22,359
Unhook me.

1253
01:24:31,160 --> 01:24:33,230
No, there's another one.
You'll never get it off like that.

1254
01:24:38,760 --> 01:24:41,149
I'm sorry, for everything.

1255
01:24:42,080 --> 01:24:44,799
Don't feel sorry for me.
Pity that poor Dorothy.

1256
01:24:46,640 --> 01:24:49,757
She's got the early morning teas
and the breakfast trays...

1257
01:24:50,720 --> 01:24:54,759
then get Miss Isobel down,
if there's anything in black.

1258
01:24:57,040 --> 01:24:59,600
She needs your sympathy.
I'm well out of it.

1259
01:25:01,840 --> 01:25:04,479
I would think Miss Isobel
would stay in bed tomorrow.

1260
01:25:06,280 --> 01:25:07,315
Unmarried girls

1261
01:25:07,520 --> 01:25:10,034
don't have breakfast trays.
Not in this house.

1262
01:25:13,680 --> 01:25:15,352
I wish I could help.

1263
01:25:17,280 --> 01:25:18,508
Well, you can't.

1264
01:25:34,520 --> 01:25:38,718
George says Mr. Novello
was in on it. And Sir William.

1265
01:25:40,120 --> 01:25:42,953
The point is, that Henry Denton,
he's an actor.

1266
01:25:43,160 --> 01:25:44,309
An actor?

1267
01:25:44,520 --> 01:25:47,830
He's playing a butler
in the next Charlie Chan.

1268
01:25:48,040 --> 01:25:49,792
I'd say the joke was on Lady Sylvia.

1269
01:25:50,000 --> 01:25:52,195
I hope Mr. Jennings
wasn't his model,

1270
01:25:52,400 --> 01:25:54,470
or he'd be too squiffy
to remember his lines.

1271
01:25:55,160 --> 01:25:58,630
Mrs. Croft, isn't it?
I wonder if I could

1272
01:25:59,520 --> 01:26:02,671
have a few words with you.
I'm Inspector Thom...

1273
01:26:02,880 --> 01:26:05,075
I haven't got time for this.
I'm doing the breakfasts.

1274
01:26:05,480 --> 01:26:09,758
It won't take much time.
Perhaps you have a room.

1275
01:26:10,440 --> 01:26:13,512
You better come to my room.
Bertha, I'm leaving you in charge.

1276
01:26:13,720 --> 01:26:16,837
Dorothy, make sure the menus
are on Her Ladyship's tray.

1277
01:26:17,040 --> 01:26:18,871
Get that filthy dog out of here.

1278
01:26:22,000 --> 01:26:23,353
Honestly,

1279
01:26:23,560 --> 01:26:27,075
these days the countryside
is more dangerous than Piccadilly.

1280
01:26:28,000 --> 01:26:31,709
Why a silver pantry knife?
It doesn't make sense.

1281
01:26:32,720 --> 01:26:34,392
He must have forgotten
to bring one.

1282
01:26:35,000 --> 01:26:36,991
Think of what they
have to carry about.

1283
01:26:37,200 --> 01:26:41,079
All those jemmies and torches
and skeleton keys.

1284
01:26:41,600 --> 01:26:43,955
It's a miracle anyone
ever gets burgled.

1285
01:26:44,680 --> 01:26:47,831
It's glacial in here.
Get my fur, will you?

1286
01:26:49,840 --> 01:26:52,195
Anyway, it wasn't in
the silver pantry.

1287
01:26:52,400 --> 01:26:54,595
It went missing yesterday.

1288
01:26:55,040 --> 01:26:56,553
Obviously William had it.

1289
01:26:56,840 --> 01:26:58,910
When the fellow surprised him,

1290
01:26:59,120 --> 01:27:00,997
there it was, handy as you like.

1291
01:27:03,160 --> 01:27:06,277
Are any of the others
getting up for breakfast?

1292
01:27:06,720 --> 01:27:08,631
Lady Lavinia may be.

1293
01:27:09,440 --> 01:27:12,750
That settles it. Come back
at 8:30. I'll get dressed.

1294
01:27:14,040 --> 01:27:15,792
It's the greatest bore,
of course.

1295
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:17,752
But I don't want to
miss anything.

1296
01:27:21,720 --> 01:27:22,869
When I came back last night,

1297
01:27:24,400 --> 01:27:27,153
- I found this on my table.
- What is it?

1298
01:27:31,680 --> 01:27:33,272
"This is your final warning.

1299
01:27:33,680 --> 01:27:35,398
If I've not received an offer..."

1300
01:27:37,120 --> 01:27:38,997
Freddie". What a stupid idiot!

1301
01:27:39,440 --> 01:27:42,273
At least he's off your back.

1302
01:27:42,480 --> 01:27:44,914
No one will give him
a job to shut up.

1303
01:27:48,640 --> 01:27:51,552
He's quite a bonny lad.

1304
01:27:52,120 --> 01:27:54,076
What's he up to these days?

1305
01:27:54,280 --> 01:27:55,269
He's dead.

1306
01:27:57,120 --> 01:27:58,678
I don't know what I can tell you.

1307
01:27:58,920 --> 01:27:59,989
Shouldn't you be looking for

1308
01:28:00,200 --> 01:28:01,315
signs of a break in?

1309
01:28:01,520 --> 01:28:04,273
I understand that no one has
served Sir William

1310
01:28:04,480 --> 01:28:06,550
longer than you have.

1311
01:28:06,920 --> 01:28:10,117
I better be off.
Might not see you again.

1312
01:28:11,560 --> 01:28:13,039
I'm only staying

1313
01:28:13,240 --> 01:28:14,275
till the police give the nod.

1314
01:28:15,480 --> 01:28:16,549
But Elsie,

1315
01:28:18,560 --> 01:28:21,518
you're not in any difficulty?

1316
01:28:21,800 --> 01:28:23,916
Apart from having
no home and no job?

1317
01:28:24,640 --> 01:28:26,631
No, there's no worries there.

1318
01:28:27,560 --> 01:28:31,235
Yes, I was forgetting.
You were much cleverer than I was.

1319
01:28:31,640 --> 01:28:33,039
You'll be fine.

1320
01:28:37,600 --> 01:28:39,397
What will Lady Sylvia do?

1321
01:28:39,600 --> 01:28:42,990
I'd set up in London
as a glamorous widow

1322
01:28:43,360 --> 01:28:45,749
with all the gentlemen
chasing me for my money.

1323
01:28:45,960 --> 01:28:47,313
I wouldn't. I grew up in London.

1324
01:28:48,360 --> 01:28:51,272
- Is that where the orphanage was?
- On the edge. Isleworth.

1325
01:28:52,080 --> 01:28:53,195
And don't you get homesick?

1326
01:28:53,400 --> 01:28:56,517
Not if you never had a home.
Heard about Weissman's valet?

1327
01:28:56,720 --> 01:28:58,119
- What about him?
- Turns out he's a fraud.

1328
01:28:58,520 --> 01:29:02,354
- He isn't Scottish at all.
- I could've told you that.

1329
01:29:03,360 --> 01:29:06,238
- Who is he then?
- Is he the murderer?

1330
01:29:06,440 --> 01:29:08,556
Worse than that. He's an actor.

1331
01:29:10,400 --> 01:29:13,517
Yes, I want you to wake him up.
How else do I talk to him?

1332
01:29:15,040 --> 01:29:17,110
Yes, right. What did he say?

1333
01:29:17,720 --> 01:29:20,188
He's talking about
Clara Bow again? Listen.

1334
01:29:20,600 --> 01:29:23,990
Tell Sheehan I think
Clara Bow is a nice person,

1335
01:29:24,200 --> 01:29:28,432
and I don't want her
in the fucking movie.

1336
01:29:29,320 --> 01:29:32,630
This bastard's death
may have saved my bacon.

1337
01:29:32,840 --> 01:29:35,149
For God's sake, be quiet.
What the matter with you?

1338
01:29:39,680 --> 01:29:40,715
Arthur.

1339
01:29:41,520 --> 01:29:43,556
- Are these tomatoes?
- Yes, my Lady.

1340
01:29:43,760 --> 01:29:45,352
That's exactly what I want.

1341
01:29:47,080 --> 01:29:49,071
- Good morning.
- Morning, dear.

1342
01:29:50,000 --> 01:29:54,596
Have you heard? That frightful
inspector won't let anyone leave.

1343
01:29:55,520 --> 01:29:59,274
Another day of Weissman
shouting down the telephone.

1344
01:30:00,840 --> 01:30:02,193
He has some work problems

1345
01:30:02,400 --> 01:30:03,674
in Los Angeles.

1346
01:30:04,040 --> 01:30:06,998
I must say he conducts
his affairs very oddly.

1347
01:30:07,280 --> 01:30:10,909
Coming downstairs, I thought
I was in a Marseilles bar.

1348
01:30:11,480 --> 01:30:14,631
Excuse me. I'm expecting
a really important phone call.

1349
01:30:14,840 --> 01:30:17,149
- Would you get me when it comes?
- Very good, sir.

1350
01:30:17,360 --> 01:30:20,989
Thank you. And I'd like
tomato and eggs.

1351
01:30:21,720 --> 01:30:23,233
Of course, sir, but...

1352
01:30:24,000 --> 01:30:26,719
perhaps you would prefer to
choose for yourself, sir?

1353
01:30:26,920 --> 01:30:29,275
What do you mean,
like cafeteria style?

1354
01:30:30,200 --> 01:30:32,509
The Englishman is never
waited on at breakfast.

1355
01:30:33,640 --> 01:30:36,632
Really? That's interesting,
because an American is.

1356
01:30:37,600 --> 01:30:38,828
I'm gonna make a note of that.

1357
01:30:42,440 --> 01:30:44,715
- Good morning.
- Morning.

1358
01:30:50,880 --> 01:30:52,677
I'd like some coffee, Jennings.

1359
01:30:53,640 --> 01:30:54,834
There it is.

1360
01:30:55,640 --> 01:30:57,551
You haven't made
a lot of friends here.

1361
01:30:58,840 --> 01:31:01,400
Good. Good morning,
ladies, gents.

1362
01:31:03,920 --> 01:31:05,399
I wonder, excuse me...

1363
01:31:06,160 --> 01:31:09,232
- Will Lady Sylvia be down soon?
- I shouldn't think so.

1364
01:31:09,440 --> 01:31:12,637
She has breakfast in her room,
then usually goes for a ride.

1365
01:31:13,800 --> 01:31:16,234
But she won't be doing that
this morning, will she?

1366
01:31:19,000 --> 01:31:20,069
Oh, I see.

1367
01:31:21,520 --> 01:31:26,116
In that case, Lady Trentham,
I wonder if you'd be kind enough

1368
01:31:26,320 --> 01:31:28,914
to join us for some questions?

1369
01:31:29,520 --> 01:31:32,717
If you wish, Inspector.
I won't be much help.

1370
01:31:34,160 --> 01:31:36,993
But on a day like this
we all have to pull our weight.

1371
01:31:38,200 --> 01:31:40,509
Mr. Denton made a chump
out of Mr. Jennings.

1372
01:31:40,720 --> 01:31:42,836
Never mind that.
Did you hear about Sir William?

1373
01:31:43,160 --> 01:31:46,516
Apparently he wasn't stabbed.
I mean, he was,

1374
01:31:46,880 --> 01:31:48,359
but that's not why he died.

1375
01:31:49,200 --> 01:31:51,998
He was poisoned.
That's what killed him.

1376
01:31:52,640 --> 01:31:54,198
Inspector told Mrs. Croft.

1377
01:31:54,480 --> 01:31:58,155
They don't know why the killer
stabbed him but he was dead.

1378
01:31:58,360 --> 01:31:59,952
That's why there was no blood.

1379
01:32:00,920 --> 01:32:02,717
Dead bodies don't bleed.

1380
01:32:03,240 --> 01:32:05,515
Trust Sir William
to be murdered twice.

1381
01:32:07,880 --> 01:32:11,316
He wasn't murdered,
not that sort of murder.

1382
01:32:12,480 --> 01:32:15,950
Some ruffian broke in
thinking the library was empty.

1383
01:32:16,880 --> 01:32:19,917
Sir William surprised him
and paid the price for it.

1384
01:32:20,920 --> 01:32:22,831
- And very tragic it is too.
- I can't see that.

1385
01:32:23,040 --> 01:32:24,155
I mean...

1386
01:32:24,360 --> 01:32:27,511
ruffians don't poison people
and then stab the corpses.

1387
01:32:27,960 --> 01:32:29,234
Apart from anything else,

1388
01:32:29,440 --> 01:32:31,192
they're usually in a hurry
to get away, aren't they?

1389
01:32:32,320 --> 01:32:33,389
What are you suggesting?

1390
01:32:33,600 --> 01:32:34,749
Nothing, just...

1391
01:32:34,960 --> 01:32:36,075
Just what?

1392
01:32:36,960 --> 01:32:40,509
It looks like Sir William
was killed deliberately.

1393
01:32:41,280 --> 01:32:42,998
No wonder they won't let us go.

1394
01:32:44,000 --> 01:32:46,230
Tough luck on anyone
who's got secrets to hide.

1395
01:32:49,760 --> 01:32:51,876
Now they've cancelled
the shooting,

1396
01:32:52,080 --> 01:32:54,435
muggins here has to pull
a luncheon out of the hat.

1397
01:32:54,680 --> 01:32:56,398
- Is Her Ladyship back yet?
- No.

1398
01:32:56,720 --> 01:32:58,472
Then she'll take what she gets.

1399
01:32:59,520 --> 01:33:01,112
Why would anyone kill Sir William?

1400
01:33:01,320 --> 01:33:03,709
He wasn't exactly
Father Christmas.

1401
01:33:04,440 --> 01:33:05,919
Get on with your work.

1402
01:33:06,120 --> 01:33:07,997
And take that filthy dog out.

1403
01:33:09,880 --> 01:33:11,916
He made a few enemies in his time.

1404
01:33:12,120 --> 01:33:15,715
- "Enemies"? When?
- Is this before the war?

1405
01:33:15,920 --> 01:33:17,751
When you were a factory worker?

1406
01:33:17,960 --> 01:33:20,838
I was never a factory worker.

1407
01:33:21,160 --> 01:33:23,310
I was a cook in
one of his factories.

1408
01:33:23,680 --> 01:33:25,636
He had two in Isleworth
and two in Twickenham,

1409
01:33:25,840 --> 01:33:28,149
all full of girls,
so you can imagine.

1410
01:33:28,360 --> 01:33:30,999
Weren't factory girls risky?
Suppose they had complained?

1411
01:33:31,200 --> 01:33:32,633
Who to exactly?

1412
01:33:33,520 --> 01:33:35,511
What if they got in trouble?

1413
01:33:36,640 --> 01:33:39,552
- What sort of trouble?
- Take these. Whites only.

1414
01:33:40,440 --> 01:33:42,590
Didn't happen very often.
When it did,

1415
01:33:43,320 --> 01:33:44,992
he'd arrange to have it adopted.

1416
01:33:45,800 --> 01:33:47,472
What if you didn't want it adopted?

1417
01:33:48,280 --> 01:33:50,840
- Say you wanted to keep it?
- Then you lost your job.

1418
01:33:51,040 --> 01:33:54,749
Take my word, he was
a hard-hearted, randy old sod.

1419
01:33:58,040 --> 01:34:01,316
- Come in, I'm Inspector...
- This is all

1420
01:34:01,520 --> 01:34:04,592
too tiresome and absurd.
He's making the most dreadful fuss.

1421
01:34:04,800 --> 01:34:07,314
I'd like to ask the young lady
some questions.

1422
01:34:08,000 --> 01:34:10,878
I'm not leaving,
if that's what you think.

1423
01:34:11,520 --> 01:34:14,353
Does it bother you
if Lady Trentham stays?

1424
01:34:14,560 --> 01:34:15,993
- Why should it?
- Sir, someone's

1425
01:34:16,200 --> 01:34:17,872
traipsed a load of mud in here.

1426
01:34:18,080 --> 01:34:19,308
Not now, Dexter.

1427
01:34:20,920 --> 01:34:21,989
I understood there was

1428
01:34:22,200 --> 01:34:24,236
some difficulty between

1429
01:34:24,440 --> 01:34:27,432
- Sir William and your employer.
- This is too vulgar.

1430
01:34:27,840 --> 01:34:31,037
I wasn't aware of that.
They got on well.

1431
01:34:31,240 --> 01:34:33,595
- You were not conscious...?
- There's a broken coffee cup.

1432
01:34:33,800 --> 01:34:36,075
They have people to
clear these things up.

1433
01:34:36,280 --> 01:34:37,713
On with your job.

1434
01:34:39,560 --> 01:34:40,709
So you were not aware of

1435
01:34:40,920 --> 01:34:43,229
trouble over the matter of
an allowance?

1436
01:34:43,800 --> 01:34:45,552
An allowance, I might add,

1437
01:34:45,760 --> 01:34:47,910
that Sir William's death
has now made secure.

1438
01:34:49,880 --> 01:34:52,269
What allowance would that be, sir?

1439
01:35:00,720 --> 01:35:01,869
There you are.

1440
01:35:03,120 --> 01:35:04,519
Have you got enough light?

1441
01:35:05,120 --> 01:35:08,795
Black on black. We don't
want you going blind.

1442
01:35:09,400 --> 01:35:12,392
They've got to be done.
Outside staff

1443
01:35:12,960 --> 01:35:14,359
need them for the funeral.

1444
01:35:14,560 --> 01:35:18,792
Sorry this business with Elsie
has landed you with so much work.

1445
01:35:19,000 --> 01:35:21,560
That's what comes of being reliable.

1446
01:35:21,760 --> 01:35:24,672
Never mind me.
Mr. Jennings...

1447
01:35:24,880 --> 01:35:27,917
have you spoken to
the police again?

1448
01:35:29,400 --> 01:35:30,674
Not yet, no.

1449
01:35:31,200 --> 01:35:34,954
I suppose they have to
ask their questions, don't they?

1450
01:35:35,720 --> 01:35:36,869
Well, yes.

1451
01:35:37,960 --> 01:35:40,793
Will they be talking to
all of us?

1452
01:35:42,840 --> 01:35:44,273
I shouldn't think so.

1453
01:35:45,440 --> 01:35:46,589
I'll leave you to it then.

1454
01:35:46,800 --> 01:35:47,630
Mr. Jennings.

1455
01:35:50,280 --> 01:35:53,033
You know I'd say anything
you want me to.

1456
01:35:56,240 --> 01:35:57,593
- What?
- Anything

1457
01:35:57,800 --> 01:36:02,669
I don't care if it'll help you.
You've only to ask.

1458
01:36:19,400 --> 01:36:22,392
Let me pour you a cup of tea.

1459
01:36:22,600 --> 01:36:26,149
Yes, thank you. Mind putting
the milk in afterwards?

1460
01:36:27,160 --> 01:36:31,392
I don't know what came over me.
I usually put it in afterwards,

1461
01:36:31,600 --> 01:36:32,794
- but on that occasion...
- Sir.

1462
01:36:33,000 --> 01:36:35,355
Not now, thank you.
So sorry.

1463
01:36:36,040 --> 01:36:39,112
Mrs. Thompson prefers the milk
in first, so I...

1464
01:36:39,320 --> 01:36:42,039
get used to pouring for her.
Some nonsense

1465
01:36:42,240 --> 01:36:45,550
about bacteria. You know
what women are like, well, wives.

1466
01:36:46,000 --> 01:36:47,877
She's a funny old... Sugar?

1467
01:36:48,080 --> 01:36:49,559
No, thank you.

1468
01:36:56,520 --> 01:36:58,670
- Mr. Parks.
- Robert.

1469
01:36:59,520 --> 01:37:00,669
Robert, then.

1470
01:37:01,480 --> 01:37:02,674
It's just...

1471
01:37:03,480 --> 01:37:05,550
last night when you said
you'd surprise me,

1472
01:37:06,960 --> 01:37:09,633
you didn't mean anything
by it, did you?

1473
01:37:10,080 --> 01:37:11,877
Why? Don't you like surprises?

1474
01:37:14,360 --> 01:37:15,713
Mr. Stockbridge.

1475
01:37:16,320 --> 01:37:18,788
I assume you're all aware

1476
01:37:19,080 --> 01:37:20,752
that Mr. Denton

1477
01:37:21,200 --> 01:37:24,670
played a trick on us by
posing as a valet.

1478
01:37:25,560 --> 01:37:27,790
Since Sir William was aware of it,

1479
01:37:28,000 --> 01:37:31,037
it's not for anyone to criticise it.

1480
01:37:31,520 --> 01:37:34,432
However, it leaves us with
some adjustments for this evening.

1481
01:37:35,640 --> 01:37:40,156
Arthur, you'll dress Mr. Weissman.
That leaves Mr. Novello.

1482
01:37:40,360 --> 01:37:42,430
I don't want to ask you,
Mr. Probert.

1483
01:37:42,640 --> 01:37:45,438
- I don't mind.
- You've got enough on your plate.

1484
01:37:45,640 --> 01:37:49,872
- I'll do him if you like.
- That's very generous of you.

1485
01:37:50,680 --> 01:37:53,592
- I could always do it myself.
- No.

1486
01:37:53,800 --> 01:37:55,916
- It's no trouble for a night or two.
- Good.

1487
01:37:56,120 --> 01:37:57,917
Splendid. That's settled then.

1488
01:37:58,760 --> 01:38:02,036
I think we can leave Mr. Denton
to dress himself.

1489
01:38:03,760 --> 01:38:07,230
"The bastard's death may have
saved my bacon".

1490
01:38:07,880 --> 01:38:11,077
- What did he mean by that?
- Isn't it obvious?

1491
01:38:11,800 --> 01:38:12,676
Is it?

1492
01:38:12,880 --> 01:38:16,111
Perhaps the investment
Sir William had agreed

1493
01:38:16,320 --> 01:38:18,754
would have to be paid now. Sir.

1494
01:38:18,960 --> 01:38:22,635
What about the low shot
that nearly killed him?

1495
01:38:22,840 --> 01:38:24,319
- Sir.
- What is it?

1496
01:38:24,520 --> 01:38:26,750
We haven't dusted those things
for fingerprints yet.

1497
01:38:27,400 --> 01:38:28,389
Good.

1498
01:38:29,240 --> 01:38:34,234
- Might the shot have been intended?
- It nearly took his ear off.

1499
01:38:36,080 --> 01:38:38,196
Thank you.
You've been most helpful.

1500
01:38:38,400 --> 01:38:39,958
Ask Commander Meredith
to join us now.

1501
01:38:41,320 --> 01:38:45,279
You won't tell him
what I said, Inspector Thomas?

1502
01:38:46,080 --> 01:38:50,756
Thompson! Never mind.
Just go and fetch him, please.

1503
01:38:53,960 --> 01:38:54,995
Sir.

1504
01:38:59,720 --> 01:39:04,350
- We've only got this.
- Mine hasn't go any black here.

1505
01:39:04,600 --> 01:39:05,669
We've got some new ones.

1506
01:39:06,960 --> 01:39:08,757
- You're a lech.
- George.

1507
01:39:09,000 --> 01:39:09,989
They're coming in a minute.

1508
01:39:10,200 --> 01:39:11,553
The dressing bell's just gone.

1509
01:39:11,760 --> 01:39:14,593
I'm going out of my mind.
I've read my magazines twice.

1510
01:39:14,800 --> 01:39:16,756
Get something from the library,

1511
01:39:17,120 --> 01:39:19,554
even if it's "Horse and Hound".

1512
01:39:24,600 --> 01:39:26,238
Well, we are honoured.

1513
01:39:26,440 --> 01:39:29,159
In case you've forgotten,
this is the servants' area.

1514
01:39:29,360 --> 01:39:32,193
Yours is at the top of the
stairs behind that door.

1515
01:39:32,400 --> 01:39:35,472
Barnes, I just wanted to explain.

1516
01:39:35,680 --> 01:39:37,352
No explanation necessary,
Mr. Denton.

1517
01:39:37,560 --> 01:39:39,869
If you'll excuse me,
some of us have real work to do.

1518
01:39:40,080 --> 01:39:43,789
- Come on, Arthur.
- The accent was a dead give away.

1519
01:39:44,000 --> 01:39:48,278
- I was just having fun.
- Enjoy your fun in the drawing room.

1520
01:39:50,480 --> 01:39:53,119
They're afraid you'll repeat things,
be indiscreet.

1521
01:39:53,440 --> 01:39:57,069
But I'm very discreet.
I'm known in Hollywood for it.

1522
01:39:57,600 --> 01:39:58,874
My discretion.

1523
01:40:02,000 --> 01:40:06,357
- Tell Rupert, he won't give money.
- You misunderstand me.

1524
01:40:06,560 --> 01:40:08,516
And mummy wouldn't pay
five pounds to save me.

1525
01:40:10,120 --> 01:40:12,680
Poor darling, come here.

1526
01:40:13,520 --> 01:40:17,593
Don't think I'm enjoying this.
All I wanted was a job.

1527
01:40:18,520 --> 01:40:21,592
I'll give you a cheque
after dinner.

1528
01:40:27,680 --> 01:40:31,389
- Have you seen my man Parks?
- No, I've been with the police.

1529
01:40:31,920 --> 01:40:33,876
You look as if you've had
rather a pasting.

1530
01:40:34,280 --> 01:40:36,840
They kept on about
the low shot yesterday

1531
01:40:37,800 --> 01:40:38,994
and wouldn't let it go.

1532
01:40:39,760 --> 01:40:41,876
Obviously I told them it was
nothing to do with me.

1533
01:40:42,080 --> 01:40:44,753
I'm sure, but another time
try to be less greedy.

1534
01:40:44,960 --> 01:40:46,234
- Parks.
- What?

1535
01:40:47,280 --> 01:40:50,158
Attend to Mr. Novello first.
I want a word with Her Ladyship.

1536
01:40:50,400 --> 01:40:51,515
Very well, my Lord.

1537
01:40:51,720 --> 01:40:54,075
- What?
- I saw you.

1538
01:40:54,600 --> 01:40:56,272
Of course it was an accident.

1539
01:40:56,640 --> 01:41:00,349
It's hard for a short man like you
to gauge the height of the birds.

1540
01:41:06,680 --> 01:41:07,635
Mr. Meredith.

1541
01:41:08,280 --> 01:41:11,397
You haven't seen Commander Meredith
anywhere, have you?

1542
01:41:11,600 --> 01:41:13,909
He's not downstairs or in his room.

1543
01:41:14,120 --> 01:41:18,591
I washed and dressed him.
Not my fault he can't find his way.

1544
01:41:29,320 --> 01:41:31,993
- I didn't mean to disturb you.
- No, please.

1545
01:41:32,200 --> 01:41:34,873
I'm just trying
some of your jam.

1546
01:41:36,320 --> 01:41:37,594
I must be in your way.

1547
01:41:37,920 --> 01:41:40,036
No, no bother.

1548
01:41:41,840 --> 01:41:42,875
What one is that, sir?

1549
01:41:45,520 --> 01:41:47,476
It's raspberry, October '31.

1550
01:41:48,400 --> 01:41:50,038
You might like to try

1551
01:41:51,480 --> 01:41:53,596
- the strawberry one.
- Was there strawberry?

1552
01:41:59,400 --> 01:42:00,753
Are you all right, sir?

1553
01:42:02,000 --> 01:42:03,752
I've just been with the inspector

1554
01:42:05,200 --> 01:42:06,679
and I feel a little bruised.

1555
01:42:18,560 --> 01:42:20,278
Why is it, would you say,

1556
01:42:21,040 --> 01:42:23,235
that some people seem to get
whatever they want in life?

1557
01:42:24,960 --> 01:42:27,076
Everything they touch
turns to gold.

1558
01:42:28,720 --> 01:42:31,359
Whereas others can strive
and strive...

1559
01:42:32,120 --> 01:42:33,269
and have nothing?

1560
01:42:35,880 --> 01:42:37,438
Do you believe in luck?

1561
01:42:39,720 --> 01:42:42,439
Do you believe some men are lucky

1562
01:42:43,920 --> 01:42:45,717
and some men just aren't,

1563
01:42:46,880 --> 01:42:49,997
- and nothing they can do about it?
- I believe in love.

1564
01:42:50,400 --> 01:42:52,630
Not just getting it,
giving it.

1565
01:42:52,960 --> 01:42:56,236
As long as you can love somebody,
whether or not they love you,

1566
01:42:56,440 --> 01:42:58,431
then it's worth it.

1567
01:43:07,640 --> 01:43:08,959
That's a good answer.

1568
01:43:11,040 --> 01:43:12,439
I'd better go.

1569
01:43:12,640 --> 01:43:14,471
They must've finished dinner.

1570
01:43:17,160 --> 01:43:18,275
Thank you.

1571
01:43:20,280 --> 01:43:23,033
I thought the wine was
frightful tonight. Vile.

1572
01:43:23,240 --> 01:43:24,673
Jennings, old boy.

1573
01:43:25,240 --> 01:43:26,355
I'll have a bourbon.

1574
01:43:27,320 --> 01:43:30,471
We don't have bourbon.
Ordinary Scotch or single malt.

1575
01:43:31,240 --> 01:43:33,356
Ordinary for me.
I'm just an American.

1576
01:43:38,160 --> 01:43:41,277
This is not an ideal time,
but I'd like to

1577
01:43:41,480 --> 01:43:42,708
see you again.

1578
01:43:43,560 --> 01:43:45,391
Mabel is so clever
to travel light.

1579
01:43:46,360 --> 01:43:48,999
Why wear a different frock
every night?

1580
01:43:49,240 --> 01:43:52,516
- We're not in a fashion parade.
- No, and I wouldn't want to be.

1581
01:43:53,840 --> 01:43:56,229
- Excuse me.
- Difficult colour, green.

1582
01:43:56,440 --> 01:43:59,193
- What did she say?
- Very tricky.

1583
01:43:59,520 --> 01:44:01,238
- Isobel.
- Excuse me.

1584
01:44:09,440 --> 01:44:11,829
This tune used to make me cry.

1585
01:44:20,160 --> 01:44:23,994
I promise you I can
pay you back every penny.

1586
01:44:25,040 --> 01:44:26,189
I must say...

1587
01:44:26,440 --> 01:44:30,558
your guests have more
comfortable beds than servants.

1588
01:44:33,880 --> 01:44:34,835
Excuse me.

1589
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:37,194
What did Isobel give you?

1590
01:44:38,000 --> 01:44:40,355
What did Isobel give to you?
Tell me!

1591
01:44:41,240 --> 01:44:42,036
Ivor...

1592
01:44:42,640 --> 01:44:45,837
would you play something cheerful?

1593
01:44:46,040 --> 01:44:47,758
We're all quite emotional
enough as it is.

1594
01:44:51,280 --> 01:44:52,235
Excuse me.

1595
01:44:52,440 --> 01:44:54,158
Freddie, stop all your lies!

1596
01:44:55,400 --> 01:44:57,868
If you don't give it to me now,
I'll scream this house down.

1597
01:44:58,880 --> 01:45:00,393
If you don't believe me,
try me.

1598
01:45:00,600 --> 01:45:02,272
Where have you been?

1599
01:45:02,680 --> 01:45:05,433
You've missed dinner.
We can organise a tray.

1600
01:45:08,920 --> 01:45:11,275
Try buying yourself
a new frock with that.

1601
01:45:14,000 --> 01:45:16,195
- We gave up, Louisa.
- Right.

1602
01:45:16,400 --> 01:45:17,674
I'm so sorry.

1603
01:45:18,560 --> 01:45:19,629
No coffee, but I'll have...

1604
01:45:21,440 --> 01:45:25,069
- I apologise. I can't imagine...
- Son of a bitch, it was on purpose.

1605
01:45:25,480 --> 01:45:27,072
Shall I fetch you a towel?

1606
01:45:37,920 --> 01:45:39,592
- Arthur...
- Oh dear.

1607
01:45:39,800 --> 01:45:40,915
Clean this up.

1608
01:45:43,680 --> 01:45:46,990
They fished parts of her body
from the Thames.

1609
01:45:47,200 --> 01:45:50,715
- Some more tea, Constable?
- I'll take that, Bertha.

1610
01:45:50,960 --> 01:45:54,236
- Well, go on.
- No head, no hands.

1611
01:45:55,560 --> 01:45:58,199
What's the point?
Won't it all be chucked out?

1612
01:45:58,400 --> 01:46:02,439
I'll know I've left it in order.
That's all I can do now.

1613
01:46:02,760 --> 01:46:04,591
- Yeah, but he won't...
- Leave him alone.

1614
01:46:05,600 --> 01:46:08,797
George had his revenge on Denton.
Hot coffee in the lap.

1615
01:46:10,240 --> 01:46:13,710
- Poor Mr. Denton.
- I'm glad I caught you.

1616
01:46:14,760 --> 01:46:18,355
I assume the inspector won't
keep everyone beyond tomorrow.

1617
01:46:18,560 --> 01:46:22,473
- He hasn't spoken to some servants.
- Dexter. We're going home.

1618
01:46:22,680 --> 01:46:24,830
I was asking how long
our guests will be staying.

1619
01:46:25,040 --> 01:46:27,679
Mrs. Croft has meals to arrange,
and one of the maids

1620
01:46:27,880 --> 01:46:30,474
- is anxious to get away.
- No need to worry about that.

1621
01:46:30,880 --> 01:46:34,555
I've no interest in the servants,
only those connected to the dead man.

1622
01:46:35,560 --> 01:46:36,913
I see. Thank you.

1623
01:46:37,200 --> 01:46:38,633
Do you have a light, Inspector?

1624
01:46:39,720 --> 01:46:40,596
Yes.

1625
01:46:42,240 --> 01:46:44,470
I think we can
let them all go home.

1626
01:46:44,680 --> 01:46:46,352
Got their addresses after all.

1627
01:46:46,600 --> 01:46:48,875
Dexter will be here tomorrow
to confirm that.

1628
01:46:49,560 --> 01:46:52,279
But don't worry,
it doesn't end here.

1629
01:46:52,800 --> 01:46:56,190
Whoever he is, I'll find him.
I always do.

1630
01:46:57,400 --> 01:46:59,356
Inspector. Matches.

1631
01:46:59,880 --> 01:47:01,233
Yes. Thank you.

1632
01:47:04,320 --> 01:47:08,359
- Sir, it's this way.
- Yes, yes.

1633
01:47:08,680 --> 01:47:11,990
There's a way out that way,
but we'll take your way.

1634
01:47:26,760 --> 01:47:30,230
Beg your pardon, just collecting
Mr. Nesbitt's shoes.

1635
01:47:41,120 --> 01:47:43,395
These stairs are
the easiest way up.

1636
01:47:43,800 --> 01:47:45,711
- Thank you...
- George, sir.

1637
01:47:46,320 --> 01:47:47,389
George.

1638
01:47:53,280 --> 01:47:55,589
You naughty, naughty girl.

1639
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:00,194
Poor bloke.

1640
01:48:00,680 --> 01:48:04,195
We were in the ironing room
and a visiting maid came in.

1641
01:48:04,720 --> 01:48:06,551
He must think
I did it on purpose.

1642
01:48:07,160 --> 01:48:09,276
- You won't tell, will you?
- I won't tell.

1643
01:48:09,720 --> 01:48:12,359
You're lucky you're in kitchen
and not under Mrs. Wilson.

1644
01:48:12,760 --> 01:48:15,399
She'd have sniffed you out
without my help.

1645
01:48:27,880 --> 01:48:30,075
Do you think Sir William
was in love with you?

1646
01:48:30,320 --> 01:48:32,959
No, I was a bit of fun,
that's all.

1647
01:48:35,840 --> 01:48:36,909
And you?

1648
01:48:39,040 --> 01:48:41,793
No, I didn't love him.
I didn't mind him, but...

1649
01:48:44,080 --> 01:48:46,514
I liked the way he'd talk.
He only talked to me

1650
01:48:46,720 --> 01:48:50,269
because he was sick of her,
but I liked it. He said...

1651
01:48:50,480 --> 01:48:52,072
I could be what I wanted

1652
01:48:52,280 --> 01:48:53,872
as long as I wanted it enough.

1653
01:48:56,240 --> 01:48:57,719
You're not sorry then,

1654
01:48:58,040 --> 01:49:01,157
- even the way things turned out?
- No, I'm not sorry.

1655
01:49:02,520 --> 01:49:06,149
Time for a change. Who knows?
Could be the making of me.

1656
01:49:07,040 --> 01:49:10,157
What did he use to day?
Carpe Diem. Seize the day.

1657
01:49:16,520 --> 01:49:17,635
What's up?

1658
01:49:18,720 --> 01:49:20,438
What did I say?
Where are you going?

1659
01:49:29,400 --> 01:49:30,469
Who is it?

1660
01:49:33,120 --> 01:49:34,348
What are you doing?

1661
01:49:42,680 --> 01:49:45,114
Get back to your room.
You don't want to be caught here.

1662
01:49:48,720 --> 01:49:50,915
You didn't really
dislike him, did you?

1663
01:49:52,640 --> 01:49:53,709
Not really.

1664
01:49:54,800 --> 01:49:56,916
At least, not enough
to kill him.

1665
01:50:04,880 --> 01:50:06,438
You can't have.

1666
01:50:07,440 --> 01:50:08,919
You didn't know him.

1667
01:50:09,640 --> 01:50:12,154
You'd have to hate him,
and why would you?

1668
01:50:14,360 --> 01:50:16,191
Can't a man hate his own father?

1669
01:50:23,240 --> 01:50:24,832
Sir William McCordle...

1670
01:50:25,960 --> 01:50:27,359
was my father.

1671
01:50:30,160 --> 01:50:31,229
He didn't know it,

1672
01:50:32,480 --> 01:50:33,708
but he was.

1673
01:50:35,760 --> 01:50:40,311
- You said you were an orphan.
- I said I grew up in an orphanage.

1674
01:50:48,840 --> 01:50:52,515
Before I left, a group of us
broke in and took our files.

1675
01:50:54,600 --> 01:50:58,275
I found my birth certificate:
Mother's name, father unknown.

1676
01:50:58,480 --> 01:50:59,390
I found this photograph.

1677
01:51:01,080 --> 01:51:02,638
And they had my admission form.

1678
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:05,195
I was two days old.
Guess who brought me to the door.

1679
01:51:07,680 --> 01:51:09,989
- That doesn't mean he...
- Yes, it does.

1680
01:51:12,520 --> 01:51:14,875
I found out she worked
in one of his factories.

1681
01:51:17,360 --> 01:51:18,839
She wasn't the only one.

1682
01:51:21,240 --> 01:51:24,994
The authorities didn't know
or want to. They took his babies

1683
01:51:25,680 --> 01:51:27,079
and took his money.

1684
01:51:29,440 --> 01:51:31,237
What happened to your mother?

1685
01:51:32,880 --> 01:51:33,949
She died.

1686
01:51:38,720 --> 01:51:41,359
Is that why you took the job
with Lord Stockbridge?

1687
01:51:42,360 --> 01:51:43,952
To get to Sir William?

1688
01:51:45,360 --> 01:51:48,113
- To poison him?
- I didn't poison him.

1689
01:51:49,680 --> 01:51:52,592
- What?
- I didn't poison him.

1690
01:51:55,480 --> 01:51:57,277
Then you didn't kill him!

1691
01:51:58,480 --> 01:51:59,754
Did you stab him?

1692
01:52:01,600 --> 01:52:02,635
Even if you did,

1693
01:52:02,840 --> 01:52:04,353
he was already dead.

1694
01:52:04,560 --> 01:52:08,519
Whoever did it must've known.
You can't stab a corpse and not know.

1695
01:52:08,720 --> 01:52:10,915
When was the last time
you stabbed a corpse?

1696
01:52:15,480 --> 01:52:17,118
Who really murdered him then?

1697
01:52:19,120 --> 01:52:20,189
I don't know.

1698
01:52:23,280 --> 01:52:24,679
I don't care.

1699
01:52:45,840 --> 01:52:48,798
I've wanted to do that ever since
I first set eyes on you.

1700
01:53:17,160 --> 01:53:18,275
Mr. Jennings.

1701
01:53:18,560 --> 01:53:20,676
Wilson, Mrs. Wilson...

1702
01:53:27,520 --> 01:53:29,192
Dorothy. I need your help.

1703
01:53:30,080 --> 01:53:31,957
Of course, Mrs. Wilson.
Are you all right?

1704
01:53:35,080 --> 01:53:36,513
No-one must see him like this.

1705
01:53:39,400 --> 01:53:41,470
- Mr. Jennings, come on.
- Come on, Mr. Jennings.

1706
01:53:43,560 --> 01:53:47,394
- All right. Bed time.
- No. This way, Mr. Jennings.

1707
01:53:48,360 --> 01:53:49,793
Bedtime now. Come on.

1708
01:53:54,680 --> 01:53:57,672
- My reference?
- You'll get your reference.

1709
01:53:57,920 --> 01:54:00,434
Into bed now.

1710
01:54:04,320 --> 01:54:06,754
Take his trousers off,
would you Dorothy?

1711
01:54:07,520 --> 01:54:10,034
I couldn't do that,
Mrs. Wilson.

1712
01:54:10,240 --> 01:54:13,437
Take his trousers off.
Come on, girl.

1713
01:54:14,800 --> 01:54:17,268
Is Lady Sylvia?
She's not here, is he?

1714
01:54:25,880 --> 01:54:28,633
- Who is it?
- I'm ever so sorry, sir.

1715
01:54:28,840 --> 01:54:32,355
- Sorry for what?
- I'm not meant to wake you.

1716
01:54:32,560 --> 01:54:35,836
Why does everyone treat me like
one of these stupid snobs?

1717
01:54:36,040 --> 01:54:38,429
I spent half the week
downstairs with all of you.

1718
01:54:38,800 --> 01:54:40,791
You can't be
on both teams at once.

1719
01:54:45,240 --> 01:54:47,196
It's official.
They're off after breakfast.

1720
01:54:47,400 --> 01:54:49,436
Thank God for that
What about him?

1721
01:54:49,760 --> 01:54:52,354
He's going too. As soon as
he's seen Mr. Jennings.

1722
01:54:53,640 --> 01:54:55,870
Are you all right?
You sound a bit funny.

1723
01:54:56,080 --> 01:54:59,675
Just too many fags.
They'll be the death of me.

1724
01:54:59,880 --> 01:55:01,313
Here, you finish it.

1725
01:55:02,680 --> 01:55:06,389
- Did you tell the police that stuff?
- I did not. Sorry if I shock you,

1726
01:55:06,600 --> 01:55:09,068
but the plain fact is he only
got what he deserved.

1727
01:55:10,200 --> 01:55:11,428
There, I've said it.

1728
01:55:13,040 --> 01:55:14,951
I can't stop thinking about
those girls.

1729
01:55:16,200 --> 01:55:18,634
- The ones that got, you know.
- I'm not surprised,

1730
01:55:18,840 --> 01:55:20,159
the way you carry on.

1731
01:55:20,360 --> 01:55:22,476
Just see it never happens to you.

1732
01:55:23,520 --> 01:55:28,150
No, and even if it did, I couldn't
part with my baby for a job.

1733
01:55:28,920 --> 01:55:30,319
I'm very glad to hear it.

1734
01:55:32,000 --> 01:55:33,035
Who is it?

1735
01:55:33,680 --> 01:55:35,636
Don't mind me.

1736
01:55:35,840 --> 01:55:39,594
- Inspector asked me to take a look.
- Is the inspector with you?

1737
01:55:39,960 --> 01:55:41,473
We're working from

1738
01:55:41,680 --> 01:55:44,956
the station. See if we can't manage
things better from here.

1739
01:55:45,640 --> 01:55:48,438
What about the poison?
Have you traced that at least?

1740
01:55:49,280 --> 01:55:50,235
Hardly.

1741
01:55:51,360 --> 01:55:53,828
This house is a poisoner's paradise.

1742
01:55:55,000 --> 01:55:57,639
We've found the stuff
in practically...

1743
01:56:00,840 --> 01:56:01,909
every room.

1744
01:56:03,240 --> 01:56:06,312
Unfortunately, no one's got
a police record.

1745
01:56:07,680 --> 01:56:09,272
Except you, of course.

1746
01:56:10,320 --> 01:56:11,514
Perhaps the butler did it.

1747
01:56:23,200 --> 01:56:25,509
I had a brother who was
a conscientious objector.

1748
01:56:27,160 --> 01:56:28,798
He did a bit of time, too.

1749
01:56:31,200 --> 01:56:34,397
Do they know upstairs you refused
to fight and were sent to prison?

1750
01:56:37,320 --> 01:56:38,958
I'd forget about it if I were you.

1751
01:56:39,880 --> 01:56:41,757
Not everyone's cut out to be
a soldier.

1752
01:57:05,760 --> 01:57:06,954
Did you remember the others boxes?

1753
01:57:07,160 --> 01:57:10,357
- Everything's in the car.
- Wonderful.

1754
01:57:10,560 --> 01:57:12,357
Darling. Here I come.

1755
01:57:12,560 --> 01:57:15,313
- I can't wait to leave this place.
- Let's go.

1756
01:57:15,760 --> 01:57:17,716
What are we supposed to do now?

1757
01:57:18,280 --> 01:57:22,159
Freddie, do try to stop being so
frightened all the time.

1758
01:57:23,520 --> 01:57:26,990
- Have I made a fool of myself?
- Maybe, but you're my fool.

1759
01:57:27,200 --> 01:57:29,156
Anthony, I just...

1760
01:57:30,560 --> 01:57:33,074
I wanted to remind you of the
conversation we had the other night.

1761
01:57:34,360 --> 01:57:36,635
Perhaps this is not the most
appropriate moment, but

1762
01:57:36,840 --> 01:57:40,196
when you get the Sudan you'll
need an expert,

1763
01:57:40,440 --> 01:57:42,317
and I'm your man.

1764
01:57:44,120 --> 01:57:45,155
Did you ask her?

1765
01:57:45,360 --> 01:57:47,874
- No.
- I think that's a good thing.

1766
01:57:48,080 --> 01:57:49,877
Servants' hall gossip says

1767
01:57:50,080 --> 01:57:53,356
- it won't be till her mother dies.
- Jeremy, you are so...

1768
01:57:53,560 --> 01:57:55,710
If that's the case, it's too long
for you to wait.

1769
01:57:56,720 --> 01:57:57,755
You can do better.

1770
01:58:01,200 --> 01:58:02,952
Have you checked your room?

1771
01:58:03,560 --> 01:58:05,437
You mustn't leave anything behind.

1772
01:58:06,040 --> 01:58:07,758
I'm sure mummy's going to sell
the house.

1773
01:58:08,240 --> 01:58:09,229
Isobel.

1774
01:58:09,440 --> 01:58:10,998
Isobel! Isobel!

1775
01:58:12,360 --> 01:58:13,759
Kent's taking over the studio.

1776
01:58:14,880 --> 01:58:17,678
He loves Charlie Chan
and he hates Winfield Sheehan.

1777
01:58:17,920 --> 01:58:19,069
No more rewrites

1778
01:58:19,280 --> 01:58:20,474
and I can cast whoever I like.

1779
01:58:20,680 --> 01:58:23,433
- That was painless, wasn't it?
- No it wasn't.

1780
01:58:24,600 --> 01:58:25,828
Not for me, anyway.

1781
01:58:27,920 --> 01:58:29,638
Careful. Watch yourself.

1782
01:58:37,480 --> 01:58:38,674
Do they know?

1783
01:58:38,920 --> 01:58:41,036
- No.
- Do you think they might notice?

1784
01:58:41,240 --> 01:58:42,389
I don't care.

1785
01:58:42,760 --> 01:58:43,715
Hey, you there.

1786
01:58:43,920 --> 01:58:45,399
Where are you going?

1787
01:58:46,760 --> 01:58:47,829
To the station.

1788
01:58:48,360 --> 01:58:49,839
You want a ride to London?

1789
01:58:53,520 --> 01:58:54,748
Sure, why not?

1790
01:58:56,720 --> 01:58:58,517
- Hop in.
- Thank you.

1791
01:59:02,480 --> 01:59:03,549
There you go.

1792
01:59:04,040 --> 01:59:05,758
Good luck.

1793
01:59:06,200 --> 01:59:09,875
- Don't do anything I wouldn't do.
- That gives me room for maneuver.

1794
01:59:13,760 --> 01:59:15,352
Keep your hands to yourself.

1795
01:59:16,480 --> 01:59:17,833
You Brits don't have a sense
of humor, do you?

1796
01:59:18,720 --> 01:59:20,836
We do if something's funny, sir.

1797
01:59:21,080 --> 01:59:22,672
- Mr. Jennings.
- Be quick about.

1798
01:59:23,720 --> 01:59:24,994
Honestly,

1799
01:59:25,200 --> 01:59:28,909
it's getting so expensive leaving
something for the housemaids,

1800
01:59:29,120 --> 01:59:30,473
one might as well take a suite

1801
01:59:30,680 --> 01:59:31,829
at the Ritz.

1802
01:59:33,120 --> 01:59:37,079
What about William's little maid?
I never saw her again after dinner.

1803
01:59:37,480 --> 01:59:38,595
Elsie?

1804
01:59:38,960 --> 01:59:41,599
- She's gone.
- It's a pity really.

1805
01:59:41,800 --> 01:59:45,429
It was a good idea to have
someone whose sorry he's dead.

1806
01:59:47,720 --> 01:59:51,190
- Did you have a nice ride?
- I feel guilty. Everyone's gone.

1807
01:59:52,200 --> 01:59:54,919
Apart from you and Louisa.
Why don't you stay for luncheon?

1808
01:59:55,120 --> 01:59:58,192
No. Best be off.
Leave you in peace.

1809
02:00:00,000 --> 02:00:03,754
You will telephone about
the funeral plans?

1810
02:00:04,760 --> 02:00:07,797
- Don't come if it's a bore.
- Of course I'm coming.

1811
02:00:08,720 --> 02:00:11,871
- What will you do with this place?
- I don't know.

1812
02:00:12,960 --> 02:00:14,234
Will you keep it?

1813
02:00:15,800 --> 02:00:17,028
It's so difficult.

1814
02:00:18,080 --> 02:00:20,594
Does one really want
the bother nowadays?

1815
02:00:23,120 --> 02:00:24,838
I could shut it up

1816
02:00:25,040 --> 02:00:28,077
and make a decision when
my head stops spinning.

1817
02:00:28,280 --> 02:00:30,555
Mrs. Wilson could manage till
you're ready.

1818
02:00:30,760 --> 02:00:33,274
She could manage all right.
Let's not worry about that.

1819
02:00:33,640 --> 02:00:37,918
She'll get rid of
the wretched Mrs. Croft.

1820
02:00:38,120 --> 02:00:40,111
- Why are those two such enemies?
- I don't know.

1821
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:43,639
They were both workers in
one of William's sweatshops.

1822
02:00:44,520 --> 02:00:46,556
Mrs. Croft was the senior then.
She was the cook.

1823
02:00:46,800 --> 02:00:49,439
And Mrs. Wilson,
a lowly factory worker.

1824
02:00:49,680 --> 02:00:52,513
Now that she's gone up,
poor Crofty can't abide it.

1825
02:00:53,400 --> 02:00:54,515
Usual rubbish.

1826
02:00:55,040 --> 02:00:57,110
Was there ever a Mr. Wilson?

1827
02:00:57,320 --> 02:00:59,038
- I can't imagine it.
- Nor could I.

1828
02:00:59,960 --> 02:01:01,871
Although, funnily enough,
I think there must have been.

1829
02:01:02,920 --> 02:01:04,478
Really? You amaze me.

1830
02:01:05,840 --> 02:01:09,310
She might have changed her name,
but when she worked with William

1831
02:01:09,520 --> 02:01:13,832
she was something different.
Parks or Parker or Parkinson,

1832
02:01:14,160 --> 02:01:15,275
or something like that.

1833
02:01:18,600 --> 02:01:19,589
Come in.

1834
02:01:22,920 --> 02:01:25,275
- You're busy.
- I was checking the linen rotation.

1835
02:01:25,480 --> 02:01:29,314
If left it to the maids,
twenty sheets would be rags.

1836
02:01:39,600 --> 02:01:40,828
Why did you do it?

1837
02:01:48,280 --> 02:01:49,918
How did you know it was him?

1838
02:01:50,960 --> 02:01:55,431
- The name or the photograph.
- Yes, the photograph.

1839
02:01:57,120 --> 02:02:00,635
It's a miracle that survived.
His mother put it into his blanket.

1840
02:02:00,840 --> 02:02:03,513
I suppose she wanted him to have
something of hers.

1841
02:02:03,720 --> 02:02:05,278
Does he know what happened to her?

1842
02:02:07,040 --> 02:02:09,952
They said she died just after
he was born.

1843
02:02:11,080 --> 02:02:12,991
She didn't die, she gave him away.

1844
02:02:16,720 --> 02:02:19,632
He promised the boy would be
adopted, that he knew the family.

1845
02:02:20,000 --> 02:02:20,955
Turns out we all

1846
02:02:21,160 --> 02:02:23,913
clung to that dream.
All us girls.

1847
02:02:24,680 --> 02:02:26,432
A better start in life
for our children.

1848
02:02:28,200 --> 02:02:32,557
And he was dumping them
in some God-forsaken place.

1849
02:02:34,280 --> 02:02:35,679
And I believed him.

1850
02:02:37,280 --> 02:02:40,590
I suppose it was easier that way.
My sister never forgave me.

1851
02:02:42,520 --> 02:02:44,909
- Your sister?
- Mrs. Croft. She's my sister.

1852
02:02:45,120 --> 02:02:47,634
Didn't you know?
She kept hers.

1853
02:02:48,280 --> 02:02:51,590
It was very hard for her.
She lost her job and the baby died.

1854
02:02:52,360 --> 02:02:53,793
Scarlet fever.

1855
02:02:55,240 --> 02:02:58,118
I made him take her back.
She never forgave me for that either.

1856
02:02:59,000 --> 02:03:01,468
But even if Robert is your son,

1857
02:03:01,680 --> 02:03:03,989
how did you know that
he meant to harm his father?

1858
02:03:06,080 --> 02:03:09,436
What gift separates a good servant
from the others?

1859
02:03:10,640 --> 02:03:12,517
It's the gift of anticipation.

1860
02:03:13,440 --> 02:03:16,477
I am a good servant.
I'm better. I'm the best.

1861
02:03:16,680 --> 02:03:17,829
I'm the perfect servant.

1862
02:03:18,240 --> 02:03:22,552
When they're hungry, food is ready.
When they're tired, a bed.

1863
02:03:23,240 --> 02:03:25,196
I know before they know it.

1864
02:03:29,720 --> 02:03:31,119
Are you going to tell him?

1865
02:03:33,320 --> 02:03:36,517
Why? What purpose
would it possibly serve?

1866
02:03:40,880 --> 02:03:43,917
- What if they find out what happened?
- Not much a crime

1867
02:03:44,120 --> 02:03:45,838
to stab a dead man, is it?

1868
02:03:46,480 --> 02:03:49,552
They can never touch him.
That's important. His life.

1869
02:03:51,760 --> 02:03:52,909
And your life?

1870
02:03:55,000 --> 02:03:57,798
I'm the perfect servant.
I have no life.

1871
02:04:03,680 --> 02:04:06,069
- Her Ladyship's leaving now, miss.
- Thank you, George.

1872
02:04:11,800 --> 02:04:13,597
You should go now, Miss Trentham.

1873
02:04:29,840 --> 02:04:34,072
- Here you are.
- Most generous. Thank you.

1874
02:04:34,280 --> 02:04:37,317
Let us know if there's
anything we can do to help.

1875
02:04:38,200 --> 02:04:41,636
- Are you going to go away at all?
- Not once the shooting's finished.

1876
02:04:42,120 --> 02:04:44,839
- Thank you for your help last night.
- You don't have to thank me.

1877
02:04:45,120 --> 02:04:47,395
I would kill for Mr. Jennings
if I had to.

1878
02:05:12,960 --> 02:05:14,996
Don't cry, Jane, they'll hear you.

1879
02:05:20,120 --> 02:05:21,155
Come on.

1880
02:05:23,240 --> 02:05:24,798
You did what you felt

1881
02:05:25,000 --> 02:05:26,558
was best for him at the time.

1882
02:05:27,400 --> 02:05:28,753
I see that now.

1883
02:05:30,880 --> 02:05:31,869
Lizzie...

1884
02:05:33,360 --> 02:05:34,873
I've lost him.

1885
02:05:36,120 --> 02:05:39,078
I've lost him.
He'll never know me now.

1886
02:05:39,840 --> 02:05:44,118
- My boy.
- At least your boy's alive.

1887
02:05:46,200 --> 02:05:47,918
He's alive.

1888
02:05:48,800 --> 02:05:50,358
That's what matters.

1889
02:06:06,400 --> 02:06:08,755
- So, you're leaving.
- Yes.

1890
02:06:12,520 --> 02:06:13,635
Goodbye then.

1891
02:06:16,240 --> 02:06:18,231
- Goodbye.
- Parks.

1892
02:06:21,640 --> 02:06:23,870
Goodbye, my dear. Chin up.

1893
02:06:27,440 --> 02:06:29,237
Heavens, what a relief to be going.

1894
02:06:30,320 --> 02:06:32,311
It'll take me a month to recover.

1895
02:06:32,520 --> 02:06:35,557
Mary, Mary dear...
Do you think if there's

1896
02:06:35,760 --> 02:06:37,876
a trial I might have to testify

1897
02:06:38,440 --> 02:06:39,953
in court? Or you?

1898
02:06:40,880 --> 02:06:42,677
I can't think of anything worse.

1899
02:06:42,880 --> 02:06:47,271
Imagine a person being hanged
because of what one said in court.

1900
02:06:48,280 --> 02:06:52,068
I know. And what purpose could it
possibly serve anyway?

1901
02:07:00,120 --> 02:07:01,269
Goodbye.

1902
02:07:25,200 --> 02:07:28,397
Somewhere there's another land

1903
02:07:28,880 --> 02:07:32,316
different from this world below,

1904
02:07:32,520 --> 02:07:33,338
far more mercifully planned

1905
02:07:35,840 --> 02:07:39,310
than the cruel place we know.

1906
02:07:40,560 --> 02:07:44,314
Innocence and peace are there

1907
02:07:45,000 --> 02:07:48,629
all is good that is desired,

1908
02:07:49,360 --> 02:07:54,070
faces there are always fair

1909
02:07:55,040 --> 02:07:59,431
love grows never old nor tired.

1910
02:08:02,040 --> 02:08:06,795
We shall never find that lovely land

1911
02:08:07,080 --> 02:08:09,469
of Might-Have-Been,

1912
02:08:10,280 --> 02:08:13,670
I can never be your king

1913
02:08:13,880 --> 02:08:17,429
nor you can be my queen.

1914
02:08:18,280 --> 02:08:22,114
Days my pass,
and years my pass

1915
02:08:22,320 --> 02:08:26,029
and seas may lie between.

1916
02:08:27,440 --> 02:08:32,230
We shall never find that
lovely land

1917
02:08:32,600 --> 02:08:35,672
of Might-Have-Been.
